âœ… Scripted interview line (say verbatim)

â€œIâ€™ll first think of a brute-force solution where I calculate the maximum for every window, but that would be inefficient. To optimize it, Iâ€™ll use a monotonic deque so that each element is processed only once, achieving linear time complexity.â€

ğŸ§  Clear Intuition (Very Simple)

We are given an array nums and a window size k

For every contiguous window of size k, we must find the maximum element

Sliding the window one step at a time

ğŸ‘‰ Key problem:
If we recompute max for every window â†’ slow (O(nÂ·k))

ğŸ‘‰ Smart idea:
Maintain a deque that always keeps elements:

In decreasing order

Front of deque = maximum of current window

ğŸš€ Optimal Approach: Monotonic Deque (Sliding Window)
Why Deque?

We need:

Remove elements from front (out of window)

Remove smaller elements from back (useless for max)

Deque supports both ends in O(1)

âœ… Algorithm (Step-by-step)

Traverse array with index i

Remove indices from front if they are out of window

Remove indices from back if their value is smaller than current

Add current index

Once window size â‰¥ k, record max from front

ğŸ’» C++ Code (WITH INLINE DRY RUN ğŸ‘‡)
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        deque<int> dq; // stores indices
        vector<int> ans;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {

            // 1ï¸âƒ£ Remove elements OUTSIDE the window
            // Window range = [i-k+1, i]
            if (!dq.empty() && dq.front() == i - k) {
                dq.pop_front();
            }

            // 2ï¸âƒ£ Remove smaller elements from back
            // They can never be maximum
            while (!dq.empty() && nums[dq.back()] < nums[i]) {
                dq.pop_back();
            }

            // 3ï¸âƒ£ Insert current index
            dq.push_back(i);

            // 4ï¸âƒ£ Start recording answer when window size hits k
            if (i >= k - 1) {
                ans.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);
            }

            /*
            ğŸ” INLINE DRY RUN (nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], k=3)

            i=0 â†’ dq=[0] â†’ window not ready
            i=1 â†’ remove 1<3 â†’ dq=[1]
            i=2 â†’ dq=[1,2] â†’ max=nums[1]=3
            i=3 â†’ dq=[1,2,3] â†’ max=3
            i=4 â†’ remove smaller â†’ dq=[4] â†’ max=5
            i=5 â†’ dq=[4,5] â†’ max=5
            i=6 â†’ remove smaller â†’ dq=[6] â†’ max=6
            i=7 â†’ remove smaller â†’ dq=[7] â†’ max=7
            */
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

â±ï¸ Time & Space Complexity

Time: O(n) â†’ each element pushed & popped once

Space: O(k) â†’ deque stores window elements

ğŸ” Pattern Recognition (VERY IMPORTANT)
ğŸ§© This problem is a classic:

Sliding Window + Monotonic Deque

Use this pattern when:

Window size is fixed

You need max / min in each window

Brute force feels repetitive

